and comparing it to 1. There is always an integer "M" that satisfies

"ƒ"("k", "n", "p") is monotone increasing for "k" < "M" and monotone decreasing for "k" > "M", with the exception of the case where ("n" + 1)"p" is an integer. In this case, there are two values for which "ƒ" is maximal: ("n" + 1)"p" and ("n" + 1)"p" − 1. "M" is the "most probable" ("most likely") outcome of the Bernoulli trials and is called the <a href="Mode%20%28statistics%29">mode</a>. Note that the probability of it occurring can be fairly small.

